    "summary": "The National Union of Somali Journalists (NUSOJ) demands Puntland authorities free reporter Suways Ga'ayte and drop all charges, citing a pattern of intimidation against independent media.",
    "content": "The National Union of Somali Journalists (NUSOJ) has renewed its criticism of the Puntland administration, urging the immediate release of independent journalist Suways Ga'ayte and the dismissal of all criminal charges against her. In a statement issued Friday, the union accused local judicial bodies of misusing the law to suppress critical reporting. Ga'ayte's detention has become a focal point in the ongoing tensions between Puntland's government and the media, with NUSOJ warning that such actions threaten press freedom in the region.\n\nThe case against Ga'ayte, a reporter known for independent coverage, has drawn attention to what NUSOJ describes as a growing trend of harassment directed at journalists in Puntland. The union claims that authorities are employing legal measures to target reporters who question official actions. This incident is not isolated; previous cases have involved journalists being detained or facing charges after reporting on sensitive topics related to governance or security.\n\nPuntland, a semi-autonomous state in northeastern Somalia, has seen periodic clashes between its leadership and media organizations. The regional government maintains that its actions are in line with legal protocols, while activists and press freedom groups argue that these measures stifle dissent. The standoff reflects broader challenges in Somalia, where journalists often operate under threat from both state and non-state actors.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this development underscores the fragile state of media freedom in their homeland. Many diaspora members rely on independent Somali outlets for news, and restrictions on reporting can limit the flow of reliable information. The case also highlights the risks faced by journalists in Somalia, reminding diaspora communities of the ongoing struggles for democratic rights and accountability.\n\nNUSOJ's call for Ga'ayte's release has been echoed by international press freedom advocates, who urge Puntland to uphold constitutional guarantees of free expression. As the situation evolves, the union says it will continue to monitor closely and push for legal protections for journalists.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/10/journalists-union-raps-puntland-authorities-over-arrest-of-reporter/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journalists-union-raps-puntland-authorities-over-arrest-of-reporter",
